    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2260282839" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2260282839" />
    <a title="Efka" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22832688-efka"><img alt="Efka" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1449145657p2/22832688.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2260282839?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Efka" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Efka" href="/user/show/22832688-efka">Efka</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22832688-efka?shelf=detectives">detectives</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22832688-efka?shelf=dystopian">dystopian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22832688-efka?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22832688-efka?shelf=cyberpunk">cyberpunk</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2260282839" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16292311367691088261">Cyberpunk had never been a genre I really loved. That doesn&apos;t mean I don&apos;t like it – I do. I just don&apos;t read a lot of it. My perfect cyberpunk, which I compare everything to, is... No, it&apos;s not Blade Runner, wrong guess. It&apos;s Deus Ex: Human Revolution. And I was very, very happy to find out that Altered Carbon is in the same league with Deus Ex.<br/><br/>Sure, there are notable differences, mostly regarding the main characters, Adam Jensen and Takeshi Covacs, as the former is heavily augmented with artifi</span>
  <span id="freeText16292311367691088261" style="display:none">Cyberpunk had never been a genre I really loved. That doesn't mean I don't like it – I do. I just don't read a lot of it. My perfect cyberpunk, which I compare everything to, is... No, it's not Blade Runner, wrong guess. It's Deus Ex: Human Revolution. And I was very, very happy to find out that Altered Carbon is in the same league with Deus Ex.<br /><br />Sure, there are notable differences, mostly regarding the main characters, Adam Jensen and Takeshi Covacs, as the former is heavily augmented with artificial limbs and organs and is more like a cyborg than a human being, while the latter is definitely very human, though cloning, sleeving, re-sleeving and adding biochemical modifications to those bodies are very transhuman... things. In any case, both of them are cool, smart, and extremely combat-effective. And not the nicest guys, too. That's what I like most about them. I have to admit, Adam Jensen, as a game character, can be both a goodie two-shoes and the incarnation of evil, based on your play style. But MY Adam is neither of them. My Adam is a lone wolf, who values human life, but has no qualms if he has to take it away. And that makes him so much similar to Takeshi. Takeshi <b>Kovač</b>, ffs, not some Covacs.<br /><br />Richard K. Morgan spent a lot of time (and paper, probably) creating a living, realistic world, but that time had been spent really well. It's been a while since I read a book with such an immersive world building – it's brutal, violent and ruthless, and at the same time it is brimming with new tech, new worlds, virtual reality, AI and near-immortality. And that is potentially an explosive mixture – if the plot is good, the book that can succesfully incorporate such polar differences is destined for greatness.<br /><br />Guess what? The plot IS GOOD.<br /><br />Morgan's style of writing is also something I enjoyed immensely. He's not your typical sci-fi writer, a shy nerd with a good upbringing, afraid to use an F word or getting a blush after being asked if there's some sex in his books. Richard does not shy away from lustful and extended sex scenes, provides you with an abundance of dick jokes and his in-depth knowledge of torture techniques actually raises a few questions for me. Like, how the hell did you come up with them? Have previous experience in the field? And so on. :)<br /><br />Altered Carbon had been a long read for me. It took me almost a month to finish. There were a couple of other books while reading this one, quite a few non-reading days (or weekends, so to say), and last but not least some real life happened to happen, if you can believe it, but make no wrong assumptions – this book hooked me almost instantly and it took just some 15-20% to realise that, barring some real fuckup by the author, this will be a five star read. And it is. Now off to disappoint myself – Netflix, brace yourself, here I come.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16292311367691088261" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


